## Conditional Statements in C

C supports several types of conditional statements that control the flow of execution based on certain conditions.

### if-else Statement

```c
int age = 18;
if (age >= 18) {
    printf("You are an adult.\n");
} else {
    printf("You are not an adult.\n");
}
```

The code above checks if the person is 18 or older and prints the appropriate message.

### else if Statement

The `else if` statement can be used to check multiple expressions:

```c
int day = 3;
if (day == 1) {
    printf("Monday\n");
} else if (day == 2) {
    printf("Tuesday\n");
} else if (day == 3) {
    printf("Wednesday\n");
} else {
    printf("Unknown day\n");
}
```

This code checks the value of the `day` variable and prints the corresponding day name.

## Loops in C

Loops are used to execute a block of code repeatedly. C supports `for` and `while` loops.

### for Loop

A `for` loop is commonly used for iterating through a sequence:

```c
for (int i = 0; i < 5; ++i) {
    printf("%d\n", i);  // Outputs: 0, 1, 2, 3, 4
}
```

> **Remember:** In C, indexing starts at 0, not 1.

### while Loop

The `while` loop continues to run as long as a condition is true:

```c
int i = 0;
while (i < 5) {
    printf("%d\n", i);
    ++i;
}
```

Be careful with while loops to ensure they eventually terminate - always make sure the condition will eventually become false.

## Functions in C

Functions are reusable blocks of code designed to perform specific tasks. Here's how to create and call functions in C:

### Basic Function Example

```c
int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}

int main() {
    int result = add(10, 20);
    printf("Result: %d\n", result);  // Outputs: 30
    return 0;
}
```

This defines a function named `add` that takes two parameters and returns their sum.

### Default Parameters

Unlike some modern languages, C does not support default parameters natively. Alternative approaches include:

```c
// Using multiple functions
void greet_default() {
    printf("Hello, World\n");
}

void greet(char* name) {
    printf("Hello, %s\n", name);
}

// Or using a macro
#define GREET(name) printf("Hello, %s\n", (name) ? (name) : "World")
```

These approaches provide functionality similar to default parameters found in other languages.

## Conditional Statements

C++ supports several types of conditional statements that control the flow of execution based on certain conditions.

### if-else Statement

```cpp
int age = 18;
if (age >= 18) {
    std::cout << "You are an adult." << std::endl;
} else {
    std::cout << "You are not an adult." << std::endl;
}
```

The code above checks if the person is 18 or older and prints the appropriate message.

### else if Statement

The `else if` statement can be used to check multiple expressions:

```cpp
int day = 3;
if (day == 1) {
    std::cout << "Monday" << std::endl;
} else if (day == 2) {
    std::cout << "Tuesday" << std::endl;
} else if (day == 3) {
    std::cout << "Wednesday" << std::endl;
} else {
    std::cout << "Unknown day" << std::endl;
}
```

This code checks the value of the `day` variable and prints the corresponding day name.

