## Functions

Functions are reusable blocks of code designed to perform specific tasks. Here's how to create and call functions in C++:

### Basic Function Example

```cpp
int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}

int main() {
    int result = add(10, 20);
    std::cout << "Result: " << result << std::endl;  // Outputs: 30
    return 0;
}
```

This defines a function named `add` that takes two parameters and returns their sum.

### Function with Default Parameters

You can define functions with default parameter values:

```cpp
void greet(std::string name = "World") {
    std::cout << "Hello, " << name << std::endl;
}

int main() {
    greet();          // Outputs: Hello, World
    greet("Alice");   // Outputs: Hello, Alice
    return 0;
}
```

Default parameters make functions more flexible by allowing arguments to be optional.

## 6. Conditional Statements in Java

Java supports several types of conditional statements that control the flow of execution based on certain conditions.

### 6.1 if-else Statement

```java
int age = 18;
if (age >= 18) {
    System.out.println("You are an adult.");
} else {
    System.out.println("You are not an adult.");
}
```

### 6.2 Switch Statement

A `switch` statement can be used as an alternative to `if-else` when testing multiple conditions.

```java
int day = 3;
switch (day) {
    case 1:
        System.out.println("Monday");
        break;
    case 2:
        System.out.println("Tuesday");
        break;
    case 3:
        System.out.println("Wednesday");
        break;
    default:
        System.out.println("Unknown day");
}
```

## 7. Loops in Java

Loops are used to execute a block of code repeatedly. Java supports three types of loops: `for`, `while`, and `do-while`.

### 7.1 for Loop

A `for` loop is commonly used when you know how many times a block of code should run.

```java
for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    System.out.println(i); // Outputs: 0, 1, 2, 3, 4
}
```

### 7.2 while Loop

The `while` loop continues to run as long as a condition is true.

```java
int i = 0;
while (i < 5) {
    System.out.println(i);
    i++;
}
```

### 7.3 do-while Loop

A `do-while` loop runs at least once, even if the condition is false.

```java
int i = 0;
do {
    System.out.println(i);
    i++;
} while (i < 5);
```

## 8. Functions in Java

Functions, also called methods, are reusable blocks of code designed to perform specific tasks. Here's how to create and call methods in Java:

### 8.1 Basic Function Example

```java
public class Calculator {
    public static int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int result = add(10, 20);
        System.out.println("Result: " + result); // Outputs: 30
    }
}
```

### 8.2 Function Overloading

Java allows you to define multiple methods with the same name but different parameter lists, known as method overloading.

```java
public class Calculator {
    public static int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    public static double add(double a, double b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(add(5, 10));      // Outputs: 15 (int version)
        System.out.println(add(5.5, 10.5));  // Outputs: 16.0 (double version)
    }
}
```

## 6. Conditional Statements in JavaScript

JavaScript supports several types of conditional statements that control the flow of execution based on certain conditions.

### 6.1 if-else Statement

```javascript
let age = 18;
if (age >= 18) {
    console.log("You are an adult.");
} else {
    console.log("You are not an adult.");
}
```

### 6.2 else if Statement

The `else if` statement can be used to check multiple expressions:

```javascript
let day = 3;
if (day == 1) {
    console.log("Monday");
} else if (day == 2) {
    console.log("Tuesday");
} else if (day == 3) {
    console.log("Wednesday");
} else {
    console.log("Unknown day");
}
```

## 7. Loops in JavaScript

Loops are used to execute a block of code repeatedly. JavaScript supports `for` and `while` loops.

### 7.1 for Loop

A `for` loop is commonly used for iterating over a sequence (like a list or range):

```javascript
for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    console.log(i);  // Outputs: 0, 1, 2, 3, 4
}
```

### 7.2 while Loop

The `while` loop continues to run as long as a condition is true:

```javascript
let i = 0;
while (i < 5) {
    console.log(i);
    i++;
}
```

## 8. Functions in JavaScript

